\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Usual definition of the Reynolds number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are working at the Kolmogorov scale, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Re\approx1$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Re$
\end_inset

 is the Reynolds number.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The usual formulation of the Reynolds number is :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Re=\frac{VL_{c}}{\nu}\label{eq:re_first}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the velocity of the flow (m/s), 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic linear dimension and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=10^{-6}$
\end_inset

m
\begin_inset Formula $^{2}$
\end_inset

.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is the kinematic viscosity of the fluid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We first define 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{c}$
\end_inset

 as the dimension of the cube corresponding to the Kolmogorov scale.
 In the ocean, this corresponds to scales between 0.1 and 1 cm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "barton_impact_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $V\approx10^{-4}$
\end_inset

 m.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
However, we can also define a length 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{v}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the equivalent sphere diameter, i.e.:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{array}{cccc}
 & \frac{4}{3}\pi\left(\frac{L_{v}}{2}\right)^{3} & = & L_{c}^{3}\\
\Leftrightarrow & L_{v} & = & 2L_{c}\left(\frac{3}{4\pi}\right)^{1/3}\\
\Leftrightarrow & L_{v} & = & 1.24\text{ cm}
\end{array}\label{eq:re_lv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

If we use 
\begin_inset Formula $V\approx\nu/L_{v}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\approx8.1\times10^{-5}$
\end_inset

 m.s
\begin_inset Formula $^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 The smallest wavenumber of the flow is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{2\pi}{L}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{K}=\frac{L}{2\pi}$
\end_inset

 provides another possible dimension, which then leads to 
\begin_inset Formula $V=6.4\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset

.
 That's the option that we chose for the ReScience paper, following earlier
 discussions (including larger wavenumbers).
 
\end_layout

